<XMLDocContent PageName="cobalt.logging.LogManager" Title="LogManager class" xmlns="http://www.cobaltrenderer.com/schema/XMLDocSchema.xsd">
  <Paragraph>
    <PageRef PageName="cobalt.logging.Welcome">Home</PageRef> ->
    LogManager
  </Paragraph>
  <Section Title="Declaration">
    <Code Language="C++"><![CDATA[class LogManager;]]></Code>
  </Section>
  <Section Title="Description">
    <Paragraph>
      The <TypeRef>LogManager</TypeRef> class is the standard implementation object that creates loggers, owns log targets, and filters messages before forwarding them to those targets.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      A manager-level <PageRef PageName="cobalt.logging.ILogger.SeverityFilter">SeverityFilter</PageRef> provides the first filtering stage. Each target added through <PageRef PageName="cobalt.logging.LogManager.AddLogTarget">AddLogTarget</PageRef> can also have its own filter, allowing different targets to receive different severities.
    </Paragraph>
    <Note Type="Important">
      <Paragraph>
        A <PageRef PageName="cobalt.logging.Logger">Logger</PageRef> created by this object stores a reference to the manager. The manager must outlive every logger created from it.
      </Paragraph>
    </Note>
    <Note Type="Important">
      <Paragraph>
        Logger instances are safe to use concurrently from multiple threads. The log manager serializes message delivery, and target registration and severity filter access are safe to use concurrently as well.
      </Paragraph>
    </Note>
  </Section>
